This notebook will be used to:

  1. Do exploratory analysis on the dataset scraped in the notebook 01_Scraper.ipynb such as:
    • compute statistics about the textual data of the 10-K files stored into the json files.
    • show the distribution of the companies in the dataset
    • show the evolution of the number of words and of the Gunning Fog Index (readability measure) of the 10-K files over the period of analysis.
  2. Compute Guning Fog Index and lexical diversity
  3. Compute and Assess a doct2vec model.
  4. Compute similarity score (cos-sim) using the doc2vec model.
  5. Apply finBert to the data to compute Management's tone
  6. Run regression Analysis.

1. Structual Analysis and Descriptive Statistics

1.1. Textual Analysis

1.1.1. Structural Analysis

We created a class named PreProcessor() based on Bengfort, Bilbro and Ojeda (2018: Chapter 3) (see file Functions.py) that will allows us to have a clear structural picture of the textual content of the 10-K files. This class contains severals functions, being one of them the describe() function that, among other things, counts the number of words, the number unique words (tokens), the number of sentences, the number of "complex words", the lexical diversity and calculates the Gunning Fog Index (GFI). These metrics are separated by items when applicable and also computed at a (whole) document level, i.e. considering the whole 10-K.

Given a document (10-K files) $d$ and its section (or item) $i$, the Gunning Fog Index for a specific section is computed as:

\begin{align} GFI_{i,d}&=&\left[\frac{\text{total number of words}_{i,d}}{\text{total number of sentences}_{i,d}}+\frac{\text{total number of complex words}_{i,d}}{\text{total number of words}_{i,d}}*100\right]*0.4 \tag {1.1} \label{eq:1.1} \end{align}

At a document level, the index $i$ is dropped. Complex word is defined as any word with more than two syllables.

The lexical diversity (lexdiv) is defined as the ratio of the total number of unique words (tokens) divided by the number total number words. Say:

\begin{align} lexdiv_{i,d} = \frac{\text{total number of unique words (tokens)}_{i,d}}{\text{total number of words}_{i,d}} \tag {1.2} \label{eq:1.2} \end{align}

Our starting point are the 10-K json files stored in json format. The start_description() function of the mentioned class opens all the files in the directory, which are stored in a dictionary manner (json). Each key is an section (more specifically an item) of the 10-K file. So the function iterate over the items, break them into sentences, remove when specified bullet points, breaks, digits and punctuations and apply the mathematical operations. The reason for the removal of the punctuations, digits and similar tokens is that they are not condiered by the computation of the Gunning Fog Index. In order to count the syllables of the words, we use the pyphen-module.

Notice that at a first moment, the function is applied to every 10-K file in the directory. Independently whether a company will be kept in the data-set or not.

Given that some companies write this section by referencing to another section, we will only keep files that have at least 3 sentences in their MD&A. When this is not the case, the whole company will be excluded from the data set in order to keep the balance of the panel.

The values displayed by the output above are:

  • filename: the file used to compute the statistics
  • item: gives information whose items the statistics belong to. For the statistics related to the whole document, the item has value 'Overall'.
  • intems_count: the number of items in the document. Value is only defined for statistics related to the whole document, say, when item = 'Overall'
  • sents: the number of sentences in the item or document.
  • words: the number of words (tokens) returned by the wordpunct_tokenizer from NLTK module. It should be noted that punctuation, special characters and digits were not considered as words.
  • vocabulary: the number of unique tokens in the item or document.
  • lexdiv: a metric for text richness. Defined to be the ration between the total number of unique words (tokens) and the total number of words, being a value in interval $\left[0;1\right]$. The closer to 1, the more richer the text.
  • complex: the total number of complex words as defined by the GF-index.
  • GF: Gunning Fox index, used as a measure of readability.

1.1.2. Statistics

In this section we will divide the data set created at the end of Section 1.1.1., i.e. 02_Analysis_Ch1_CorpusStructuralDescriptionCleaned.csv into two further data-sets, one containing the structural metrics for the a given 10-K report as a whole (where items = "Overall") and another containing only the MD&A sections; we then compute some descriptive statistics to understand the distribution of the metrics, and specially how the total number of words and the Gunning Fog Index evolved over time.

As in a latter stage we will be visualizing the data divided by industries, we will use the last dataset (called Scraper_Ch6_AggregatedFinal.csv) created in hte 01_Scraper.ipynb notebook to obain the industries of the companies. The dataset has a column with the cik that can be used in conjunctution with the cik stored in the file name in the dataset df_text_structure that can be used to join them both. We also create a column with the filing year of the reports in order to be able to study the time-evolution of the metrics. The year of submission can be inferred by using the accession number of a file (the second part in the filename column); e.g. the file name 0000798287_accn0001437749-23-006150.json has the pattern cik_accn_10digits-year-6digits, where year here is the year of submission. Hence, we can and will get the dates from the file-name.

next, we create a function that will return only the complex words (words with at least 3 syllables)

In [430]:
def create_complex_list(df, text_col = 'raw_text'):
    
    def count_syllables(word):
        """
        Function is used to count the syllables of a word. It is applyed to compute GF-Index
        Arguments:
            - word: the word we want to compute the number of syllabes.
        """
        dic = pyphen.Pyphen(lang='en_US')  
        syllables = dic.inserted(word).count('-') + 1
        return syllables
    # iterate over the dataset
    sentences = df['raw_text'].tolist()
    complex_list = []
    for sentence in tqdm(sentences, desc = 'creating complex list'):
        tokens = [token for token in wordpunct_tokenize(sentence) if token.isalpha()]
        complex = [token for token in tokens if count_syllables(token) is not None and count_syllables(token) > 2]
        if complex:
            complex_list.append(' '.join(complex))
    
    return complex_list

2. Creating a Sentiment Index

2.1. Application of finBert to MD&A's

We will use this section to apply finBert trained by Huang et. al (2022) to the MD&A Sections of the 10-K files stored in our directory in order to come up with a sentiment index that will be used as a proxy as Management's tone (See notebook 01_Scraper.ipynb to understand the data collection). The reason why we use finBert is that it was the best preforming model among all others that we trained and tested (See notebook 03_Models for further details on the models training and testing methods as well as the dataset used for their purposes).

It is important to notice that sentiment analysis with finBert needs to be done at a sentence level. As financial reports contain by nature many more "neutral" than sentiment carrying sentences, finBert would assess almost all (if not all) Management Discussions of having a neutral sentiment, if we applied the model on the whole text. Moreover, finBert does not accept more than 512 tokens at once.

So the first step will be to transform the MD&A stored in json-format in the directory to sentences. We will not do any further preprocessing on the data but bullet-points and line breaks removal. If we check the performance of finBert in the 03_Models.ipynb notebook, we will find that finBert performed better in the data containing digits and punctuations, indicating that finBert uses all textual elements to infer the sentiment of a phrase (it understands the syntatic and the semantic structure of the phrases).

We created a class named PreProcessor() (as described at the beginning of Section 1) that, among other things, allows us to transform the texts into sentences using the nltk function sent_tokenize().

Given a directory, the function will open all the json files in that directory and return the item segmented in sentences that has been passed as an argument to the function.

def relabel_sentiment(x, label = False):
    
    """
    Function returns the numerical labels as defined above, if argument label is passed to True, then it will return the textual interpretation
    """
    if 'Negative' in x:
        if label:
            return 'Negative'
        return int(-1)
        
    if 'Neutral' in x:
        if label:
            return 'Neutral'
        return int(0)
        
    if 'Positive' in x:
        if label:
            return 'Positive'
        return int(1)

2.2. Computation of MD&A-Polarity (Management's Tone)

Polarity is a measure to guage the sentiment in a phrase, sentence or document. It was first used based on a dictionary approach. Let $Pol$ represent polarity, $N_{p}$ be the number of positive words in a sentence/document and $N_{n}$ be the number of negative words, polarity is computed as:

\begin{align} \text{Pol} = \frac{N_{p}-N_{n}}{N_{p}+N_{n}} \end{align}

For our purpose, we do some modification in this measure, as we predicted sentiment at sentence instead of at a word level. We compute the polarity in a document (item 7 of the 10-K file) as being

\begin{align} \text{Pol}=\frac{\#\text{Postive Sentences}-\#\text{Negative Sentence}}{\#\text{Postive Sentences}+\#\text{Negative Sentences}} * 100 \end{align}

If all sentences of a given MD&A is neutral, we assign polarity equals to 0. As we do not need the neutral sentences to compute polarity, we start by removing them from the dataset. This is cause the companies that have all neutral sentences to be completely dropped. We will add them back to the dataset and assign a polarity of zero in later stage.

We multiply polarity by hundread to scale it up, such that polarity becomes a number between -100 and 100. We create a new dataset called df_pol to store the results.

Notice once we drop the columns containing the neutral sentences, we will only have sentences that are either positive (labeled as 1) or negative (labeled as -1). So polarity can be easily computed by grouping the dataset by file-name then taking the mean value of the "labels" and multiplying it by 100.

3. Computation of Document Similarity
(Doc-to-Vec and Cosine Similarity Approach)

3.1. Data Pre-Process

One of our hypothesis is that poor performing companies will have less readable reports than those companies that perform(ed) well in the period of report. We argue that, if managers are trying to hide their poor performance, than they will also write reports that are not consistent/ similar over time, as otherwise investors would get familiar with the type of writing of the manager and be able to understand the "hidden" nuances. Thus, we control in the regression analysis (in section 5) for document similarity between reports of the same company. We will be using the so called cosine similarity, hypothesis will link company performance and cost of debt with the "readability" of their reports. We argue that the GFI will have an interaction with the document similary as an index to assess similarity of the MD&A of company $i$ between year $t$ and $t-1$.

In order to be able to compute the cosine similarity, we need to come up with a numerical vector representation of the text. For this regard, we will train a doc2vec model. Other than vectors representation like bag of words vectorizes the words as having the same distance in the vector space, such that phrases containing different meanings will have the same vector representation, given that the same words are used (e.g. "dog chases cat" and "cat chases dog"). doctovec on the other hand is capable of learning which words belong together of capturing semantics in the texts, such that similar documents will be close in the vector space. (More about the model can be found here.

Gensim offers a tutorial of how to build such models. (see notebook 01_Scraper.ipynb) and not only those files belonging to the currently 394 companies in our data set.

We first build a model, assess it and then compute the cosine similarity between the documents in a later stage. We will start by reading in all items 7 for the companies stored in our directory and then keep only the files belong to the 394 companies that we kept in the dataset so far.

# We create another function to paralize the process
def parallelize_cleantext(df, processes = os.cpu_count(), text_column = 'raw_text'):
    """
    Function is used to parallelize the clean_text function (below)
    """
    # copy the dataframe
    df = df.copy(deep = True)
    # get text column
    column_index = df.columns.get_loc(text_column)
    nlp = spacy.load("en_core_web_sm")
    def clean_text(file_info, remove_specialchar = True, lower_text = True, lemmatize = True, lower_case = True, remove_sw = True):
        """
        Function will return the cleaned text
        """
        index = file_info[0]
        text = file_info[1]
        #print(index, text)
        
        if remove_specialchar:
            #pass
            text = re.sub(r'[^A-Za-z0-9\s]', ' ', text)
        if lower_text:
            text = text.lower()
    
    
        tokens = word_tokenize(text)
        
        if remove_sw:
            non_stopwords = [word for word in tokens if word.lower() not in nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english')]
            text = ' '.join(non_stopwords)
        
        return index, text
    # given a dataframe with the texts we will yield the text rowwiese
    def yield_row(df):
        for row in df.itertuples():
            index = row.Index
            text = row._asdict()[text_column]

            yield index, text

    gen = yield_row(df)

    with ProcessPool(processes = processes) as pool:
        results = list(tqdm(
            pool.imap(clean_text, gen), total = len(df), unit = 'it', desc = 'Cleaning text'
        ))


    for result in results:
        index, cleaned_text = result
        df.at[index, 'cleaned_text'] = cleaned_text

    return df

def tag_corpus(df, tokens_only = False, text_col = 'cleaned_text', id_col = 'ID_FilingYear'):
    df = df.copy(deep = True)
    text_index = df.columns.get_loc(text_col)
    id_index = df.columns.get_loc(id_col)

    for i in range(0, df.shape[0]):
        tokens = gensim.utils.simple_preprocess(df.iloc[i, text_index])
        if tokens_only:
            yield tokens
        else:
            # For training data, add tags
            yield gensim.models.doc2vec.TaggedDocument(tokens, [df.iloc[i, id_index]])

Assessing the Model

We will assess the model according to the description given in gensim's website. We use the same data we trained the model to infer the most the most similar vector. We expect that the most similar vector $i$ predicted by the model is the vector $i$ itself itself, and that the second most similar is not nearly as similar as the first one.

In [12]:
ranks = []
second_ranks = []
for doc_id in tqdm(range(len(train_corpus)), desc='Ranking doc-similarity'):
    inferred_vector = model.infer_vector(train_corpus[doc_id].words)
    tag = train_corpus[doc_id].tags[0]
    sims = model.dv.most_similar([inferred_vector], topn = len(model.dv))
    rank = [docid for docid, sim in sims].index(tag)
    ranks.append(rank)
    second_ranks.append(sims[1])

def compute_similarity(df, model, id_col = 'ID_FilingYear'):
    """
    Function will return a matrix of cosine similiary for the companies in the dataset (similarity between their own 10-K files)
    Argument:
        df: a dataframe containing the tags used in the model.
        model: gensims doc2vec (trained) model
        id_col: the column in the dataframe containing the tags used in the doc2vec model
    """
    
    # get the id column as a list
    id_list = sorted(df[id_col].tolist())
    # now split all the values in this list using _ the left side is the company id
    # the right side is the year (we only want to have the year)
    years = [int(id.split('_')[1]) for id in id_list]
       
    # drop duplicates and sort the list
    years = sorted(list(set(years)))

    # now create a dataframe where the id_list are the index and the years are the columns
    df = pd.DataFrame(columns = years, index = id_list)
   

    # now we iterate over the company list and over the years
    for id in tqdm(id_list, desc = 'computing cos-similiarity'):
        for year in years:
            # create the tag
            comp_id = id.split('_')[0]
            tag = comp_id + '_' + str(year)
            # one of the tags is the same as the id
            cos_sim = cosine_similarity(model.dv[id].reshape(1, -1), model.dv[tag].reshape(1, -1))
            # now add the similarity score to the dataframe (recall that years are the columns and id are the indices)
            df.at[id, year] = cos_sim[0][0]

    # it is clear that in our dataset set there will be repetation, the similarity between a a file in 2016 with 2017 is the same 
    # as the similarity of 2017 with 2017. The dataset is a wide format, we bring it to a long format
    df = df.reset_index().melt(id_vars = 'index', var_name = 'sim_ij', value_name = 'sim_t-1')
    # the index column will contain the former indices and the var_name column will contain the years
    # so sim index = 0_2016 and sim_ij = 2016 is the similarity of the document of company 0 with itself
    # we create an auxiliary column with a new index where we multiply the right side of the tag and the year, the product will be the same
    # for 2016 * 2017 and 2017 * 2016, so we can drop the repetitions
    df['aux'] = df['index'].str.split('_').str.get(1).astype(int) * df['sim_ij'].astype(int)
    df['aux'] = df['aux'].astype(str)
    df['aux'] = df['index'].str.split('_').str.get(0) + "_" + df['aux']
    df.drop_duplicates(subset = 'aux', keep = 'first', inplace = True)
    df.drop(columns = 'aux')
    # further we do not want to have the similarity of a file with each self, 
    # and we only want to compute the similarity between file in period t and t-1
    # hence we can take the difference between the year of the index column and the sim_ij column
    # and keep only those values where teh difference is 1
    df['aux'] = df['index'].str.split('_').str.get(1).astype(int) - df['sim_ij'].astype(int)
    df = df[(df['aux'] == 1)]
    # we now drop the auxiliary column
    df.drop(columns = 'aux', inplace = True)
    # rename the index column to ID_FilingYear
    df.rename(columns = {'index': 'ID_FilingYear'}, inplace = True)
    return df

4. Estimation of Companies' Jensens Alpha

Jensen's alpha is the amount of return that a company created above the one predicted by the systematic-risk adjusted return. It is namely the return that is attributed to the performance of the management of a company, as this return cannot be explained by the market. In order to compute Jensen's alpha we need first to calculate the company's beta (say systematic risk). Recall CAPM equation:

\begin{align} \mathbb{E}\left[r\right]=r_{F}+\beta\left(\mathbb{E}\left[r_{M}\right]-r_{F}\right) \end{align}

where:

  • $r$: is the expected return of a given company
  • $r_{F}$: is the risk-free rate of return (proxy is the US 10y bond yield)
  • $r_{M}$: is the markt return (proxy is S&P500)
  • $\beta_{i}$: is the company's systematic risk.

Jensen's alpha is the excess return of the company above what the market would expect:

\begin{align} \mathbb{E}\left[r\right]-r_{F}=\alpha_{jensen}+\beta_{i}\left(\mathbb{E}\left[r_{M}\right]-r_{F}\right) \end{align}

Recall that a company's beta measures the sensitivity of its returns with the one of the market and is defined as $\beta=\frac{\sigma_{r,r_{M}}}{\sigma_{r_{M}}^2}$. Defining $R_{i, t} = \mathbb{E}\left[r_{i}\right]-r_{F_{t}}$ to be the return of company $i$ (or market) above the risk-free rate at period $t$ with $t = 1, \dots, 52$ (assuming that the year has 52 weeks), Jensen's alpha and the company's beta could either be computed fitting linear regression model of the type for each company and each year in the data set:

\begin{align} R_{i,t}=\alpha_{jensen\left(i,t\right)}+\beta_{i} R_{M,t} + \varepsilon_{i,t}, \end{align}

or it can be computed manually as $\widehat{\alpha}_{jensen\left(i\right)} = \bar{R}_{i} - \widehat{\beta_{i}} \bar{R}_{M}$ once we know beta (where $\bar{R}_{j}\equiv \mu_{R_{j}}$ is the mean considering all t in a given year). We choose to obtain the beta from CapitalIQ. The reason is that we want to keep as many companies as possible in the data set. Notice that we indexed the risk free rate $r_{F_t}$ with time, meaning that we allow it to float (different than standard CAPM that assumes a fixed risk-free rate of return).

We will start by importing the datasets containing share log-returns at a weekly basis obtained from yahoo finance, the one containing the betas, also computed using 52-weeks according to Capital IQ, and the one containing the US-10y bond yield at constant maturity acquired from the US-Federal Reserve (of St. Louis) and aggregated at a weekly basis. According to information of CapitalIQ, for US-Companies, the market portfolio used to compute the betas is the S&P-500, and as all companies in our data set are american companies, choosing the S&P500 to calculate the Jensens Alpha is consistent with the betas.

Notice that, in order for us to obtain the beta in capital IQ, we need to pass a date which was always chosen to be the 12/31 of a given year (for further details on the data acquisition and aggregation of share prices, bond-yield and calculation of variance and returns, see 01_Scraper.ipynb, Section 5).

Notice that the beta dataframe has two columns hold beta-values: one named beta_filing_year and one named beta_fiscal_year. The former means the beta computed with the data for the period of report, meaning that if the 10-K file was uploaded in 2016 (between feb and mar), the year of report is 2015, such that the date passed for this beta is 12/31/2015. The beta_filing_year is computed using the end of the year in which the report was submitted to the SEC, in the example 12/31/2016, we did this to facilitate data handling when we run regression analysis (more about this in Section 5).

In order to compute Jensen's alpha, we only need the betas for the report year (beta_fiscal_year), but as the our hypothesis states that, given that past performance is poor (the one for the period of report), managers will hide information when the report the performance (in the filing year). Further, there are also two columns in the dataset named Filing Date and Fiscal Date. These columns were created to to query the information about the Betas in CapitalIQ-Addin at the end of those years. They do not relate to the date that a report was filed to the SEC (only their year are the same!).

5. Regression Analysis

5.1. Joining the Data-Sets

In order to run the regression model we need to collect all variables created so far. These are:

  • The Gunning Fog-Index: measure for readability of the MD&A-sections
  • Lexical diversity: the richness of vocabulary in the MD&A-sections
  • Beta (Filing Year): measure for systematic risk of the company;
  • Cos-similarity: similarity score between the documents filed in year $t$ and $t-1$ for each company;
  • volatility: companies return-volatility;
  • Jensen's alpha: companies' return above the one expected by the market (Using CAPM-approach);
  • Accounting variables: used in later step to calculate the z-score of the company (measure for financial soundness)

We start by reading in the data sets with those variables:

As the last step, we use the variables Assets, Liabilities, Current Assets, Current Liabilities, Market Cap, Retained Earnings, Revenues, and EBIT in the df_final to compute the so-called Altman-z score, which will be used as a proxy to control for companies soundness related to accouting variables (and hence separate its effects from market-performance) and apply the log to the Market Cap-variable. The formula for Altman's z reads:

\begin{align} z_{score\left(i, t\right)} = 1.2\frac{\text{working capital}_{i, t}}{\text{Assets}_{i, t}} + 1.4\frac{\text{Retained Earnings}_{i, t}}{\text{Assets}_{i, t}} + 3.3\frac{\text{Earnings before interest and Taxes (EBIT)}_{i, t}}{\text{Assets}_{i, t}} + 0.6 \frac{\text{Market Capitalization}_{i, t}}{\text{Liabilities}_{i, t}} + 1.0 \frac{\text{Revenues}_{i, t}}{\text{Assets}_{i, t}} \end{align}

with working captital $=$ Current Assets $-$ Current Liabilities.

In [280]:
# create the variable z-score
df_final['z_score'] = (
    1.2 * ((df_final['Current Assets'] - df_final['Current Liabilities']) / df_final['Assets']) +
    1.4 * (df_final['Retained Earnings'] / df_final['Assets']) +
    3.3 * (df_final['EBIT'] / df_final['Assets']) +
    0.6 * (df_final['Market Cap'] / df_final['Liabilities']) +
    1.0 * (df_final['Revenues'] / df_final['Assets'])
)
In [282]:
# create log-market cap
df_final['logMC'] = df_final['Market Cap'].apply(lambda x: np.log(x))

5.2. Model Fit

5.2.1. Testing Hypothesis 1: Relating Poor Performance to the Gunning Fox Index

Before we begin with the actuall regression we assert our first (alternative) hypothesis:

\begin{align} H_{1}^{1}: \text{The management of poor performing companies will write "foggier" MD\&A sections in order to hide their mismanagement from the market} \end{align}

We define performance to be the market performance. Meaning that companies with a positive Jensen's alpha have achieved performance above the market expectation and those with negative jensen's alpha present performance below the one expected by the market. Hence, poor performant are those companies with a negative Jensen's alpha. We will create a dummy variable to indicate whether a company performed poorly in the period of report $poor\_perf = 1$ or not $poor\_perf = 0$.

In [314]:
file_name = 'Analysis_Ch5_FinalDataSet.csv'
df_final = pd.read_csv(tables_dir + file_name, index_col = None, dtype = {'cik': str})
# get only the variables we will need for testing our hypothesis
df_Reg = df_final[['cik', 'FiscalYear', 'sim_t_and_t_minus_1', 'polarity', 'annualized_jensens_alpha', 'ann_std_wlog_return', 'GFI', 'lexdiv', 'logMC', 'z_score', 'Industry', 'beta_filing_year', 'beta_fiscal_year']]

We now create a column with a categorical variable which equals one for negative jensens alpha and 0 otherwise.

In [315]:
df_Reg['poor_perf'] = df_Reg['annualized_jensens_alpha'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x < 0 else 0)

we will run the following regression analysis:

\begin{align} GFI_{i, t} = \alpha_{i} + \beta_{1} poor\_perf_{i, t} + \beta_{2} \log MC_{i,t} + \beta_{3} lex\_div_{i, t} + \beta_{4} z\_score_{i, t} + \beta_{5} sim_{i,t}^{(t, t-1)} + \beta_{6} \sigma_{i, t} + \varepsilon_{i, t} \tag{5.1} \label{eq:5.1} \end{align}

Where:

  • $GFI_{i, t}$: Gunning Fox Index using the MD&A section of the 10-K file for company $i$ reporting about fiscal year $t$. Detailed defintion about the $GFI$ is given in Section 1.
  • $poor\_perf$: 1 if company performed below market expectation in fiscal year $t$ and 0 otherwise.
  • $\log MC_{i, t}$: the log of company's $i$ market value at fiscal year $t$.
  • $lex\_div_{i,t}$: is the proxy for textual richness used by the management of company $i$ in its MD&A reporting about the year $t$. Definition about this value is given in Section 1.
  • $sim_{i, t}^{t, t-1}$: cosine similarity between MD&A filed by company $i$ for the report year $t$ and $t-1$.
  • $\sigma_{i,t}$: annualized stock-week-return volatility for company $i$ regarding fiscal year $t$.

Specifically, our hypothesis states that

\begin{align} H_1:\beta_{1} > 0 \end{align}

Equation $\eqref{eq:5.1}$ implies a fixed effects model for panel data. We will do a Hausman-test to assert that the model is the most appropriate for the data at hand, comparing it to the random-effects model. The test states that, if the random-effects model is the most appropriate, then there will be not significant difference between the parameters of the fixed-effects and random-effects model, nevertheless, the random effects model is also consistent (lower variance than the fixed effects) and is thus preferred. Otherwise, if we reject the null-hypothesis, the fixed-effects model is preferred, as the random effects will be biased.

In [316]:
# transform the columns containing the fiscal years to integers
df_Reg['FiscalYear'] = df_Reg['FiscalYear'].str.replace('FY', '').astype(int)

%%R -i df_Reg
library(plm)
library(stargazer)
reg_formula_h1_v1 <- "GFI ~ poor_perf + logMC + lexdiv + z_score + sim_t_and_t_minus_1 + ann_std_wlog_return "
fixed <- plm(reg_formula_h1_v1, data = df_Reg, index = c('cik', 'FiscalYear'), model = 'within')
random <- plm(reg_formula_h1_v1, data = df_Reg, index = c('cik', 'FiscalYear'), model = 'random')
test_results <- phtest(fixed, random)

test_interpretation <- function(test_results) {
    if (test_results$p.value < 0.05) {
        cat('Reject null hypothesis that coefficients of both model are equal. p-value:', test_results$p.value, '. Preferred model: fixed effects')
    } else {
        cat('Fail to reject null hypothesis that coefficients of both model are equal. p-value:', test_results$p.value, '. Preferred model: random effects')
    }
}

test_interpretation(test_results)

The output above shows that belonging to the group of poor performing companies in fiscal year $t$ causes the GFI to be higher by 0.10 points (very signficant), indicating that companies that performed poorly write somewhat foggier reports. Nevertheless this is only 0.5% higher than the mean GFI in the data set, which is 20.32.

The lexical diversity used by the manager is also correlated with the GFI, a 1% increase in lexical diversity of one percent leads to a change of 0.04 points in the GFI; the z-score on the other hand shows not significant effect not even under 10% significance level. The effect of the logMarket Value (MC) is also very significant on the GFI, meaning that bigger companies write foggier index, but is the effect probably related to the inherent complexity created by the company size, a 1% increase in the market value leads to an increase of 0.003 in the GFI. Not surprising companies that write similar MD&A reports between fiscal year $t$ and $t-1$ also have a less foggier index, an increase of 1% in similarity leads to a decrease of -0.02 points in the GFI, an increase of 1% in annualized volatility, on the other hand, leads to an increase of 0.0074 in the GFI. If we see volatility as an indication of information being absorbed by the market, then the more the market capture on information about the company, the more the company tries to hide.

In order to test the robustness of the result, we will substitute the variable poor performance in the regression above by the annualized jensens alpha, computed using weekly stocks return.

Testing Hypothesis 2: Relating Managements Tone, and Poor Performance to Companies' Future Systematic Risk

The second hypothesis states that when the management of a company had poor-performance in the fiscal year and still writes MD&A-sections with a positive tone, this company becomes risker in relation to the market (specially because of litigation risk). The assumption is that, although investors may not process the information rapidly, we should see an increase in the systematic risk of the company one year later. We state the hypothesis in form of its alternative:

\begin{align} H_{1}^{2}: \text{Poor performance along with positive management's tone in the MD\&A sections will cause future systematic risk to rise.} \end{align}

In order to test the hypothesis, we run the following regression model:

\begin{align} \beta_{i,t+1}=\gamma_{i}+\gamma_{1}poor\_perf_{i,t}+\gamma_{2}polarity_{i,t}+\gamma_{3}\log MC_{i,t}+\gamma_{4}z\_score_{i,t}+\gamma_{5}lexdiv_{i,t}+\gamma_{6}poor\_perf_{i,t}*polarity_{i,t} + \eta_{i,t} \label{eq:5.2} \tag{5.2} \end{align}

The variables have the same meaning as explained in Section 5.1., but we change the dependent variable, which is now the the systematic risk of the company in the filing-year. If $t$ represents the fiscal year (the period for which the company is reporting), the dependent variable is then $\beta_{t+1}$. We expand the regression to contain the varaible polarity (used as proxy for Management's tone) and remove the document similarity.

We are specially interest in the interaction between the variables poor\_perf and polarity. Our hypothesis states that:

\begin{align} H_{1}^{2}: \gamma_{6} > 0 \end{align}

We will now fit the regression model:

fixed_reg2 <- plm(reg_formula_h2, data = df_Reg, index = c('cik', 'FiscalYear'), model = 'within')
std_fixed_reg2 <- coeftest(fixed_reg2, vcov. = vcovHC, type = 'HC1')
# get standard errors
std2 <- std_fixed_reg2[7:12]
